Also the same thing happened to my friend but she’s straight (everybody was tellin her tht she’s gay but she wasn’t) ugghhh I just wanna live my life happy and gay but it’s not easy

snippet.textDisplay: I love u girl. Your are an amazing woman & I know so many people, esp the younger ones, will benefit greatly from your body positivity & honesty about the importance of being comfortable with our own sexuality. We all have our own truth..our own identity & individual selves to explore discover & embrace. The journey thru life is difficult at best. The years of adolescence when hormones are making us crazy in ways we can't yet begin to understand;It is a vital lesson that we need to impart to our future generations, that it's ok to be who you are no matter what. That it's ok to be confused or not know exactly how to feel or what we want, desire, & ultimately are destined deep down to be. It's ok to be attracted to anyone we see as beautiful in any way for any reason. Male or female. Period. Keep being amazingly u doll!

snippet.textDisplay: This made me cry so hard thank you Salic  for coming out and speaking your truth this has really inspired me to a 100% level. Because last year and this year has been hard for me last year my I had came out as bisexual and everyone was looking at me like I didn’t know what it meant my sister looked me as a follower and tried to say I just seen it on social media and just followed along. But that wasn’t true. And my brother has said  homophobia things to me. And told all of my cousins for no reason at all. One time he tried to make it seem like I was disgusting for liking both boys and girls he told my three year old niece that I like girls and I’m not to be trusted and took her out of the room. Where I was and than he told my other nieces and said she supporters LGBTQ if your wondering my nieces is nine and eight and three and two they don’t even know what that mean and he told one of nieces sister from another mother. I’m gay I like girls and I support the LGBTQ she is 11-12 and she didn’t know what it meant. And tried to make me feel embarrassed about my sexuality he even told my cousins but they didn’t care. And I felt hopeless and mad towards myself that year I kept telling myself I should have kept my sexuality to myself. But really how would I know at that time my brother and sister would be homophobia. I thought they would support me two of my sisters don’t know and my other sister she really doesn’t care she’s not judging me and my mom doesn’t know. But that year I was so suicidal and hated myself and my body and now this year I am so strong and doing better than I was last year and everyday I am growing I have gone to a new school and been doing so well on my tests that I’ve been having and I love myself no matter what I have a fan page that I have made friends with and they have excepted me and have help me grow and they do not judge me. And some of them are bi and lesbian and gay as well I am happy for the person that I’ve become. Because last year I was lost within myself and going through hell and I wanna thank god for getting me through that darkness and thanks to all my friends for helping me and thank me to me for finding myself and thank you for sharing this beautiful message and for those who are wondering my brother is now 15 and I’m 14 and at that time he was 14 and I was 13 I know some of you  would say well he’s young he just childish NO if I’m a year younger than him and I know right from wrong he should as well. But anyways I’m on a good path now thank you salice for sharing your story this really made my night I love you and I will always support you 💗💗💗 2020 is our year we are rising up no backing down ❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🏳️‍🌈

snippet.textDisplay:
Salice was right when she said she was gunna get heat, but she is a strong woman. It takes a lot for someone, even a big public figure, to come out like this. Even if she did come out as lesbian a long time ago, when was the first time you said you were straight? Its the same outcoming as from claiming your lesbian to bisexual as it is to being straight to bisexual. Sometimes it takes a long time for someone to find themselves. I recently came out as bisexual to my boyfriend of two years. I was so scared to tell him because of the thought of rejection and not being accepted but he was so in awe with it, he was so happy I was being honest with myself for the first time in a long time.
Some people think that Oprah or Kylie Jenner or even Michelle Obama is a big inspiration. Its all based on your opinion and you can be either so open minded or even closed minded, either one YOU CHOOSE to be, it has a lot to do with who you find inspirational. But I myself find Salice to be an inspiration. She's real. She's one to tell you straight up and be honest. Her fans are what makes her. Who would Salice Rose be without her fans? She knows the least she can do is be honest with us. So why bash somebody who is telling the truth instead of standing by their side and saying, "I'm proud of you for being true to yourself". Because you were raised to think its wrong? Its an abomination? I was. But when you have these feelings inside of you, and you feel like you have no one to turn to to let it out, you get seriously depressed and you feel so alone all the time. Since I've come out, I feel so...free...
I love you Salice Rose!!
